 of your site first</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Please report any bugs using the </strong><a href="http://wphostreviews.com/chris-contact"><strong>contact form</strong></a><strong>.&nbsp; </strong>If you can, please provide a login to your test site and I&#8217;ll try to fix any issues right away.</p>\n<h2>How do I get it?</h2>\n<p>You can download the free version of the plugin from the WordPress plugin repository. Click on the &#8216;developers&#8217; tab and select version 2.38.2.</p>\n<p>If you&#8217;re a Pro subscriber, the new version is available for download in <a href="http://wphostreviews.com/account">your account</a>. </p>\n<h2>Installation</h2>\n<p>Before installing the plugin, make a backup of your blog and your old MapPress version.&nbsp; </p>\n<ol>\n<li>Download the MapPress .zip file\n<li>From the WordPress administration screen, select Plugins -&gt; Installed Plugins.&nbsp; Find MapPress in the plugins list and click the &#8216;Deactivate&#8217; link to deactivate it.&nbsp; Then click the &#8216;Delete&#8217; link to delete it.\n<li>Select the menu Plugins -&gt; Add New.&nbsp; Click the &#8216;Upload&#8217; link at the top of the screen\n<li>Browse to find the .zip file you downloaded, then click the &#8216;install now&#8217; button\n<li>After the plugin installs, click the &#8216;activate&#8217; link to activate it\n<li>Go to the MapPress menu and check that it says version 2.38.2 at the top of the screen</li>\n</ol>\n<p>You&#8217;re all done!&nbsp; The new version should be available and working.&nbsp; You can repeat these same steps to reinstall and older version if needed.&nbsp; If there is a fatal error or a blank screen, delete the MapPress plugin directory using an FTP client to restore the site.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h2>MapPress Changes</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>POIs can now be sorted in the Map Editor.&nbsp; Just click and drag to rearrange them.\n<li>The Map Editor has been updated now includes the ability to draw polygons, lines, circles and squares\n<li>KML is now supported.&nbsp; To add a KML overlay to the map enter the URL in the &#8216;New POI&#8217; field in the Map Editor, then click the &#8216;add&#8217; button\n<ul>\n<li>As an example, try entering this as a POI (lots of other KML <a href="http://code.google.com/p/kml-samples/">examples</a> are also available from Google):\n<pre>http://kml-samples.googlecode.com/svn/trunk/kml/time/time-stamp-point.kmz</pre>\n<li>Note that you can have more than one KML file per map</li>\n</ul>\n<li>MapPress is now &#8216;location aware&#8217;.&nbsp; In the Map Editor or directions form, click &#8216;my location&#8217; to use your current location (note that accuracy is determined by your browser and connection type)\n<li>Google &#8217;45-degree imagery&#8217; is now enabled by default.&nbsp; This will show 3-D views of buildings in major cities.&nbsp; You can use parameter <code>tilt</code> to turn it off [<code>] </code>or to change the angle:<code>[mappress tilt="15"]</code>\n<li>Both qTranslate and WPML are supported for map controls and directions\n<li>The map border and shadow is now extended to include the poi list and directions by default.&nbsp;\n<li>Bug fixes: </p>\n<ul>\n<li>The directions form now shows a spinner while it''s retrieving directions\n<li>The directions form should now correctly get the focus when opened</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>New Settings</h3>\n<table border="1" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="2" width="658">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td valign="top" width="204"><strong>Setting</strong></td>\n<td valign="top" width="452"><strong>Description</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td valign="top" width="206">Map links</td>\n<td valign="top" width="451">Automatically add ''bigger map'' or ''center map'' links above the map </td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td valign="top" width="207">Map types</td>\n<td valign="top" width="450">Control which map types can be selected when viewing maps.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td valign="top" width="207">POI links </td>\n<td valign="top" width="450">Control which links appear in map POIs</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<ul></ul>\n<h3>New Shortcode Parameters</h3>\n<table border="1" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="2" width="640">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td valign="top" width="154"><strong>Parameter</strong></td>\n<td valign="top" width="150"><strong>Allowed Values</strong></td>\n<td valign="top" width="171"><strong>Default</strong></td>\n<td valign="top" width="163"><strong>Description</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td valign="top" width="158">hidden</td>\n<td valign="top" width="150">true | false</td>\n<td valign="top" width="175">false</td>\n<td valign="top" width="159">Hide the map and show a ''show map'' link instead. Click the link displays the map.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td valign="top" width="161">mapLinks</td>\n<td valign="top" width="149">bigger | center</td>\n<td valign="top" width="177">null</td>\n<td valign="top" width="157">Display links above the map </td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td valign="top" width="163">mapTypeIds</td>\n<td valign="top" width="149">roadmap | satellite | hybrid | terrain</td>\n<td valign="top" width="178">all types</td>\n<td valign="top" width="156">Allowed map types, separated by commas.&nbsp; If this parameter is omitted, all default types are allowed. If it''s empty, users cannot change the map type.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td valign="top" width="164">minZoom</td>\n<td valign="top" width="148">0-15</td>\n<td valign="top" width="179">null</td>\n<td valign="top" width="155">Minimum zoom level allowed for the map. </td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td valign="top" width="164">maxZoom</td>\n<td valign="top" width="148">0-15</td>\n<td valign="top" width="180">null</td>\n<td valign="top" width="154">Maximum zoom level allowed for the map</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td valign="top" width="164">poiLinks</td>\n<td valign="top" width="148">directions_from | directions_to | zoom</td>\n<td valign="top" width="180">"directions_to, zoom"</td>\n<td valign="top" width="154">List of links to display in POIs, separated by commas.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td valign="top" width="164">tilt</td>\n<td valign="top" width="148">0-90</td>\n<td valign="top" width="180">45</td>\n<td valign="top" width="154">Tilt for Google 45-degree imagery</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h2>MapPress Pro Changes</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href="https://developers.google.com/maps/documentation/javascript/styling">Styled Maps</a> are now supported\n<ul>\n<li>In the MapPress settings screen, enter a name and the JSON for the style from the Google <a href="http://gmaps-samples-v3.googlecode.com/svn/trunk/styledmaps/wizard/index.html">styled maps wizard</a> (note: the wizard doesn''t work in Internet Explorer).\n<ul>\n<li>Edit your style in the Google Wizard, then click ''show JSON'' to get the JSON.&nbsp; This must be pasted into the MapPress settings.&nbsp; For example, this JSON makes all roads red:<br /><code>[ { featureType: "road", stylers: [ { hue: "#ff0900" } ] } ]</code>\n<li>To automatically apply the style to all map types (such as road map, satellite, etc.) select the style under the ''default style'' setting\n<li>To make the style available for users to select as a map type, select the checkbox next to the style name in the ''Map Types'' setting\n<li>To use the style as the default for a single map, select the style in the Map Editor and save the map - or use the shortcode parameter <code>maptypeid</code>, for example: <code>[mappress maptypeid="mystyle"]</code></li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<li>Template Files can be used to adjust the formatting and content of various parts of the map\n<ul>\n<li>The default templates are in directory <code>/pro/templates</code>.&nbsp;&nbsp; Copy the template you wish to change to your theme''s directory and modify it there\n<li>You may want to use a <a href="http://codex.wordpress.org/Child_Themes">child theme</a>, otherwise WordPress will overwrite your template files whenever the theme is upgraded\n<li>The included files are:\n<ul>\n<li><code>map_layout.php</code> - the layout of the map elements (the map ''canvas'', the POI list, and directions)\n<li><code>map_directions.php</code> - the directions form\n<li><code>map_poi_list.php</code> - the POI list\n<li><code>map_poi.php </code>- the contents of the map POI infoWindows (the ''balloon'' text)</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<li>Multiple address fields are now support for geocoding, as well as latitude/longitude custom fields.&nbsp; Just select the fields in the ''geocoding'' settings section.\n<ul>\n<li>Note that if you specify <em>both </em>lat/lng fields and address field(s), the address will not be used for geocoding - but it will be used (verbatim) as the post title</li>\n</ul>\n<li>Featured image thumbnails are now shown by default in mashups linked to underlying posts\n<li>The widget and shortcode parameters for mashups have been simplified.&nbsp; Use parameter <code>marker_link</code> to link mashups to the underlying posts.\n<ul>\n<li>By default <code>marker_link</code> is set.&nbsp; This is best for mashups where each post has a map with a single location.&nbsp; The map POIs will display the post title, excerpt and featured image for the posts.\n<li>If you are trying to mashup a group of maps, use <code>[mashup marker_link="false"]</code>.&nbsp; The map POIs will display the title and body that were saved with each map POI.&nbsp; </li>\n</ul>\n<li>POI lists are now sorted (by title) by default.&nbsp; You can change the sorting if needed by using the filter ''mappress_poi_sort''.\n<li>A link parameter is available to connect all of a map''s POIs with lines (for example, to show the route of a trip).&nbsp; Use [<code>] </code>to enable it.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>New MapPress Pro Settings</h3>\n<table border="1" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="2" width="658">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td valign="top" width="204"><strong>Setting</strong></td>\n<td valign="top" width="452"><strong>Description</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td valign="top" width="206">DataTables</td>\n<td valign="top" width="451">Use the <a href="http://www.datatables.net">DataTables</a> plugin to display POI lists.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td valign="top" width="207">Map types</td>\n<td valign="top" width="450">Control which map types can be selected when viewing maps.&nbsp; Styled Map styles can also be included here.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td valign="top" width="207">POI links </td>\n<td valign="top" width="450">Control which links appear in map POIs</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td valign="top" width="207">Styled maps</td>\n<td valign="top" width="450">Enter a style name and JSON to define a style.&nbsp; The JSON can be copied and pasted from the <a href="http://gmaps-samples-v3.googlecode.com/svn/trunk/styledmaps/wizard/index.html">Google Styled Maps Wizard</a> (note that the wizard does not work with Internet Explorer).</p>\n<p>Once the style is defined, you can use the ''Default style'' setting to automatically apply it to the default map types (such as road maps and hybrid maps).</p>\n<p>You may also use the style in the Map Editor, or allow users to select it by checking it in the ''Map links'' setting section.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td valign="top" width="207">Thumbnails</td>\n<td valign="top" width="450">Check to display thumbnails in mashups that are linked to the underlying posts (where <code>marker_link = "true"</code>)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td valign="top" width="207">Thumbnail Size</td>\n<td valign="top" width="450">Specify a size name to use a pre-defined size, or enter a pixel size to force the image to resize. Using a pre-defined size is much faster but you will need a plugin to generate the thumbnails - read more in the WordPress <a href="http://codex.wordpress.org/Post_Thumbnails">Codex</a></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td valign="top" width="207">Geocoding</td>\n<td valign="top" width="450">MapPress can automatically generate maps for posts that are already geocoded.&nbsp; Use these settings to specify address or lat/lng fields to use for geocoding.&nbsp; See the section on Geocoding in the documentation for more information.</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<ul><!--EndFragment--></ul>\n<h3>New MapPress Pro Shortcode Parameters</h3>\n<table border="1" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="2" width="642">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td valign="top" width="155"><strong>Parameter</strong></td>\n<td valign="top" width="148"><strong>Allowed Values</strong></td>\n<td valign="top" width="169"><strong>Default</strong></td>\n<td valign="top" width="168"><strong>Description</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td valign="top" width="160">link</td>\n<td valign="top" width="146">line</td>\n<td valign="top" width="171">""</td>\n<td valign="top" width="166">Set to "line" to connect all map POIs with lines</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td valign="top" width="160">sort</td>\n<td valign="top" width="146">true | false</td>\n<td valign="top" width="171">true</td>\n<td valign="top" width="166">Sort mashup POI lists by title.&nbsp; If false POIs will display in the order they were saved in the Map Editor</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td valign="top" width="164">template</td>\n<td valign="top" width="144">Template file name</td>\n<td valign="top" width="171">"map_layout"</td>\n<td valign="top" width="164">Layout template file name (note: use the file name with the ''.php'' extension)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td valign="top" width="167">templateDirections</td>\n<td valign="top" width="143">Template file name</td>\n<td valign="top" width="171">"map_directions"</td>\n<td valign="top" width="163">Directions template</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td valign="top" width="169">templatePoi</td>\n<td valign="top" width="143">Template file name</td>\n<td valign="top" width="171">"map_poi"</td>\n<td valign="top" width="163">POI template</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td valign="top" width="171">templatePoiList</td>\n<td valign="top" width="142">Template file name</td>\n<td valign="top" width="170">"map_poi_list"</td>\n<td valign="top" width="162">POI list template</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td valign="top" width="172">thumbs</td>\n<td valign="top" width="142">true | false</td>\n<td valign="top" width="170">true</td>\n<td valign="top" width="162">Show thumbnails in mashups linked to posts (where marker_link = "true")</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td valign="top" width="173">thumbHeight</td>\n<td valign="top" width="141">integer</td>\n<td valign="top" width="170">64</td>\n<td valign="top" width="162">Width of thumbnails, in pixels</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td valign="top" width="174">thumbWidth</td>\n<td valign="top" width="141">integer</td>\n<td valign="top" width="170">64</td>\n<td valign="top" width="161">Height of thumbnails, in pixels</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td valign="top" width="175">thumbSize</td>\n<td valign="top" width="141">Size name</td>\n<td valign="top" width="170">""</td>\n<td valign="top" width="161">Pre-defined thumbnail size for thumbnails</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<h3>New Filters</h3>\n<p>For programmers, various new filters have been added to customize the appearance and behavior of the maps.</p>\n<p><code></p>\n<p>mappress_poi_html ( $html, $poi )</p>\n<p></code></p>\n<p>Adjust the POI contents. <code>$html</code> contains the default HTML and <code>$poi</code> contains the Mappress_Poi object representing the current POI</p>\n<p><code>mappress_poi_excerpt ( $html, $poi )</code></p>\n<p>Gets the post excerpt for mashups linked to posts. <code>$html</code> contains the default excerpt and <code>$poi</code> contains the current POI. </p>\n<p>The default excerpt is created by calling the WordPress standard function <code>the_excerpt()</code>. This function is very slow so you may want to remove the default implementation using <code>remove_filter()</code>.</p>\n<p><code>mappress_poi_links ( $links, $context, $poi )</code></p>\n<p>Gets the links to show for each POI. $links is an array of the links to display, for example <code>("directions_to", "zoom")</code>. </p>\n<p><code>$context</code> may be blank or <code>"poi"</code> (meaning links for the POI infoWindow) or <code>"poi_list"</code> indicating the POI is being displayed in a poi_list.</p>\n<p><code>$poi</code> is the current POI object.</p>\n<p><code>mappress_poi_links_html ( $html, $context, $poi )</code></p>\n<p>Use this filter to adjust the links HTML after the links have been generated. </p>\n<p><code></p>\n<p>mappress_poi_iconid ( $iconid, $poi )</p>\n<p></code></p>\n<p>Change the displayed icon. For example, you can use this filter to display a particular icon by post category. <code>$iconid</code> is the icon that would normally be displayed (or null for the default icon). <code>$poi</code> is the current POI. You can use <code>$poi-&gt;postid</code> to get the underlying post ID the POI is linked to.</p>\n<h3>New Actions</h3>\n<p>The following actions may be used:</p>\n<p><code></p>\n<p>mappress_map_display ( $map )</p>\n<p></code></p>\n<p>This action is called just before a map is displayed.&nbsp; It can be used to modify the map, for example to add or remove POIs, change icons, etc.</p>\n<p><code></p>\n<p>mappress_sort_pois ( $map )</p>\n<p></code></p>\n<p>This action is called just after a map''s POIs have been sorted.&nbsp; The default sort is by POI title.&nbsp; You can use this action to apply your own sorting routines instead - for example, sorting by a custom field.</p>\n<h2>Upgrade Notes</h2>\n<h3>You need to move your custom icons to a new directory</h3>\n<p>If you have custom icons, you must move them from the <code>/icons/</code> directory (under the MapPress installation directory) to <code>/wp-content/uploads/mappress/icons</code>. </p>\n<p>The plugin should create the uploads directory for you, but if not, you can create it manually.&nbsp; </p>\n<p>The new directory is used to prevent WordPress from deleting custom icons when MapPress is upgraded (by default WordPress deletes the entire plugin directory during each upgrade).</p>\n<h3>Mashup and widget query parameters have changed </h3>\n<p>Parameters <code>show</code> and <code>show_query</code> are now replaced by just <code>query</code>.&nbsp; You enter a custom query in this parameter or set it to <code>all</code> to show <em>all </em>posts.&nbsp; Omit this parameter or leave it blank to show current posts.&nbsp; For example:<br /><code>[mashup query="all"]</code>&nbsp; - show all posts <br /><code>[mashup query=""]</code> or <code>[mashup query="current"]</code> or just <code>[mashup]</code>– show current posts <br /><code>[mashup query="post_type=page&amp;posts_per_page=-1"]</code>&nbsp; - a custom query to show all pages</p>\n<h3>Mashup and widget title and body settings are controlled by ''marker_link'' </h3>\n<p>In earlier versions, there were separate parameters to control the mashup POI title and body.&nbsp; This is now controlled by a single parameter <code>marker_link</code>.&nbsp; </p>\n<p>Please check that your mashups and widgets are displaying properly and adjust them if needed.</p>\n<p><strong></strong></p>\n<h3>Shortcode changes </h3>\n<p>Shortcode parameter <code>initialOpenOverviewMap</code> is now <code>overviewMapControlOpened</code> (set ''true'' to initially open the overview map).&nbsp; You''ll need to update your MapPress settings and any shortcodes using this parameter.</p>\n<h3>CSS changes </h3>\n<p>CSS class <code>mapp-overlay</code> has been changed to <code>mapp-iw</code>.&nbsp; Please update any custom styles in your CSS files.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:36:"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/";a:1:{s:10:"commentRss";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:61:"http://wphostreviews.com/mappress-2-38-2-beta-available//feed";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:38:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/";a:1:{s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:1:"0";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:2;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:41:"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n\n		\n		\n			\n			\n		\n		";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:5:{s:0:"";a:7:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:30:"MapPress 2.38.1 Beta Available";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:56:"http://wphostreviews.com/mappress-2-38-1-beta-available/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:65:"http://wphostreviews.com/mappress-2-38-1-beta-available/#comments";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Tue, 22 May 2012 23:56:00 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:4:"News";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:32:"http://wphostreviews.com/?p=9698";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:358:"MapPress 2.38.1 is now available.&#160; This is the first in a series of beta versions which, despite the minor version number, will add many new functions. Please report any bugs using the contact form. How do I get it? You &#8230; <a href="http://wphostreviews.com/mappress-2-38-1-beta-available/">Continue reading <span class="meta-nav">&#8594;</span></a>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:5:"Chris";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:2859:"<p>MapPress 2.38.1 is now available.&nbsp; This is the first in a series of beta versions which, despite the minor version number, will add many new functions.</p>\n<p><strong>Please report any bugs using the </strong><a href="http://wphostreviews.com/chris-contact"><strong>contact form</strong></a><strong>.</strong></p>\n<h2>How do I get it?</h2>\n<p>You can download the free version of the plugin from the WordPress plugin repository.&nbsp; Choose the &#8216;other versions&#8217; option and select 2.38.1 (the default stable version is still 2.38).</p>\n<p>If you&#8217;re a Pro subscriber, the new version is available for download in <a href="http://wphostreviews.com/account">your account</a>. </p>\n<h2>Changes in 2.38.1:</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>The settings screen has been updated with a table to define which map controls should be displayed on maps</li>\n<li>In addition to the &#8216;traffic&#8217; control, there is now a bike routes control to highlight bike routes on the map.&nbsp; Please note that Google doesn&#8217;t offer bike routes in all areas (also, transit routes are still not available in the Google&#8217;s maps API).</li>\n<li>A new scale control can be added to show distance on the map</li>\n<li>The bike/traffic controls now better match the normal Google styling</li>\n<li>A new setting is available to force directions to particular units (metric or imperial)</li>\n<li>All calls to Google are now made using https for compatibility with security-enabled blogs</li>\n<li>All scripts are now loaded in the page footer, for better compatibility with other plugins</li>\n<li>Maps should now render properly in tab controls based on jQuery UI (Google maps display as a small square in most hidden elements, such as tabs or sliders).&nbsp; This fix works <em>only </em>for tabs based on jQuery UI; if you are using a different control or library, please see the FAQ for some tips.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>For MapPress Pro users:</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>The default map icon can now be set on the settings screen</li>\n<li>Changed: all calls to Google now use https for compatibility with security-enabled blogs<br />Changed: scripts are now loaded in the footer for better compatibility with other plugins<br />Changed: map controls now better match google styling<br />Fixed: maps should now render properly in jQuery-based tab controls.&nbsp; See the FAQ for tips on how to fix non-jQuery tabs.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Upgrade Notes:</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>You must move your custom icons</strong>.&nbsp; Rather than storing your icons in the &#8216;/icons/&#8217; directory of the plugin (where WordPress will overwrite them with each upgrade), you can now store them in &#8216;/wp-content/uploads/mappress/icons&#8217;. The plugin should create that directory for you (if not, you can create it manually).&nbsp; Please copy any custom icons to this new directory.</li>\n</ul>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:36:"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/";a:1:{s:10:"commentRss";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:61:"http://wphostreviews.com/mappress-2-38-1-beta-available//feed";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:38:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/";a:1:{s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:1:"0";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:3;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:41:"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n\n		\n		\n			\n			\n		\n		";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:5:{s:0:"";a:7:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:22:"MapPress 2.38 Released";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:48:"http://wphostreviews.com/mappress-2-38-released/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"d